\begin_layout Abstract
Neural integrators are involved in a variety of sensorimotor and cognitive
 behaviors.
 The oculomotor system contains a simple example, a hindbrain neural circuit
 that takes velocity signals as inputs, and temporally integrates them to
 control eye position.
 We combined observations of behavior, physiology, and anatomy to study
 integrator neurons.
 Two-photon calcium imaging of the larval zebrafish hindbrain was performed
 while simultaneously monitoring spontaneous eye movements.
 Integrator neurons were identified as those neurons with activities highly
 correlated with eye position, and the same neurons were then reconstructed
 from serial electron microscopic images.
 Three major morphological classes of neurons were observed: ipsilaterally
 projecting neurons located medially and rostrally, contralaterally projecting
 neurons located more laterally and caudally, and a population at the extreme
 lateral edge of the hindbrain for which we were not able to identify axons.
 Based on their somatic locations, we infer that neurons with only ipsilaterally
 projecting axons are largely glutamatergic and excitatory, whereas neurons
 with only contralaterally projecting axons are largely GABAergic and inhibitory.
 Dendritic and synaptic organization of the ipsilaterally projecting neurons
 suggest a broad sampling from inputs on the ipsilateral side.
 We observe the first conclusive evidence of synapses between integrator
 neurons, which have long been hypothesized by recurrent network models
 of integration via positive feedback.
\end_layout

