\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous attempts to understand how the integrator neurons transforms the
 'pulse'-like eye velocity signals to a 'step'-like eye position output
 have relied on combining single-neuron electrophysiology with light-microscopic
 dye fills.
 Intracellular recordings in goldfish hindbrain neurons that exhibited spiking
 correlated to eye position, followed by anatomical dye fills, show the
 axons of these neurons to send collaterals to areas where other integrator
 neurons were observed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aksay:2000cn"

\end_inset

.
 Similar anatomical observations have been observed in cats 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McCrea:1985hx"

\end_inset

 and nonhuman primates 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Steiger:1979ev"

\end_inset

.
 These observations have shaped theoretical models to propose that integration
 can be setup by recurrent excitation between these neurons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kamath:1976jm,seung_how_1996,Seung:2000kl,fisher_modeling_2013,goncalves_optogenetic_2014"

\end_inset

